```json
{
  "application": "LSF",
  "details": {
    "queue": "normal",
    "group": "farm-course",
    "job_name": "parallel[1-3]",
    "working_directory": "/nfs/users/nfs_FIXME/FIXME/hpc_workshop",
    "output_file": "logs/parallel_arrays_%I.out",
    "error_file": "logs/parallel_arrays_%I.err",
    "cpus": 2,
    "memory": "1000 MB",
    "time_limit": "30 minutes"
  }
}
```

This script is using the **LSF** (Load Sharing Facility) batch system. Here's a breakdown of the details:

* **queue:** The job will be run on the "normal" partition.
* **group:** The job will be billed to the "farm-course" group.
* **job_name:** The job name is "parallel" and will be run with 3 parallel tasks.
* **working_directory:** The job will be run in the directory "/nfs/users/nfs_FIXME/FIXME/hpc_workshop".
* **output_file:** The standard output of the job will be written to "logs/parallel_arrays_%I.out" where %I is the task index.
* **error_file:** The standard error of the job will be written to "logs/parallel_arrays_%I.err" where %I is the task index.
* **cpus:** The job will use 2 CPUs.
* **memory:** The job will require 1000 MB of memory.
* **time_limit:** The job will be allowed to run for a maximum of 30 minutes.

The script also prints some environment variables related to the LSF job.
